Following libraries are required to build the firmware:

  • NicoHood HID (https://github.com/NicoHood/HID)
  • IRLib2 (https://github.com/cyborg5/IRLib2)

Firmware is currently set up to work with Sony Bravia remote. You will have to modify firmware to make it work with some other remote. It is easily done.

  1. Download Arduino IDE (https://www.arduino.cc/en/main/software)
  2. Install IRLib2 (https://github.com/cyborg5/IRLib2)
  3. Upload "record.ino" sketch from IRLib2 examples
  4. Open Serial Monitor view in Arduino IDE
  5. Push buttons on your IR remote and watch serial port output. Write down codes for arrow buttons, OK, Return/Exit and so on
  6. Open firmware in Arduino IDE and substitute correct codes for your TV remote
  7. Save and upload modified firmware

• ATmega32U4 based Arduino Pro Micro (https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Mini-Leonardo-Pro-Micro-ATmega32U4-5V-16MHz-Module-For-Arduino-Best-Quality/32284746884.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.0.JdIPNT)

void loop() {

IN4 to Arduino pin 11

Nice and easy straight forward print that only requires 2 nuts and 2 bolts and the tripod you want to mount it on.

Because this needs the tripod mount hole threaded use 3 shells for a bit extra wall thickness to take the threads nice.

This thing has a 5.25mm hole in the lower center that needs to be threaded to accept the standard bolt on a tripod mount so you can remove it and put your expensive dslr back on when you are not using the cam mount.

2 x 30mm m3 hex head bolts are required and are inserted from top down through the upper part and 2 x m3 hex nuts will fit into the recessed hex holes in the bottom of the lower part.

To install the nuts I found it easier to push the 30mm bolt down through the lower part then wind the nut on a few thread turns and this makes it easier to pull the nut up into the retaining hole, once both nuts are in place then just unscrew the bolts and slide them through the upper part and slide the two parts together, tighten the bolts down a bit and your ready to go.

Threading the 5.25mm hole to fit the standard camera bolt was just a case of patience and holding the mount against the tripod bolt and turning the mount whilst pressing them together with light pressure untill the thread started and was looking level. Once the thread has started turn half a turn forward and quarter turn back to help clear and cut abs out of the thread and hole. Or use the correct size cutting tap if you have access to one.

**** REMEMBER ****
Once you have your cam inserted into the mount and you are tightening the 2 bolts down, tighten them down just enough to hold the cam snug, you are not putting a road wheel on a car so you do not need them just as tight.

It would matter if you attach a 75ohm external antenna when it should be 50ohm, like most of the Chinese designs (50 ohm SMA vs 75 ohm F type connectors/antennas).  For optimal broadcast power you want something like a pole antenna where you can change its length to be a fraction of the wavelength being broadcast (1/4 wave, etc.)  Having said all that, it really doesn't matter because the design that just uses a short length of ordinary wire as the antenna, works nearly as well as the pole antenna.  With the pole antenna you're able to broadcast to the entire neighborhood, which is probably illegal, vs the little wire that easily covers your house and yard.  I didn't realize this until after I published the pole antenna design.  I drove around the neighborhood and was able to go about 2/10ths of a mile before I lost the signal (using the pole antenna design).

This is an electrical heater that I made to dry silica desiccant. Its intended use case is to dry the ready-made and filled desiccant boxes without the need to remove the desiccant from the box for drying.

Link to silica desiccant box:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2245855

Electronics is pretty simple: I have used a temperature controller, power socket, and power supply. I have hooked the controller output to an old heated bed from Lulzbot Mini printer. The temperature sensor is glued to the bottom of the heated bed. In my case it was necessary to use separate temperature sensor as the one in the heated bed works within different resistance range. The lid of the chamber has a humidity/temperature module similar to those I have used in the silica desiccant boxes. This makes it easy to follow the humidity and temperature inside the chamber.

The design consist of multiple printed parts. While designing I paid special attention to make the heater simple to print but still maintain the possibility to use the heater in high temperatures. I have used the combination of regular PLA for large and complex prints and ABS for easier prints but with better temperature resistance. Finally I have used polycarbonate for the parts that are in direct contact to the heater element.

I covered the lid of the box with aluminum foil for better temperature resistance and less heat transfer through the wall.

I later modified my box to include a fan because humidity inside the chamber got too high and prevented an effective drying.

This, you'll never print, but this a tribute to how I found Makerbot. Stanley Meyer basically invented a resonant transformer, that in conjunction with a capacitor (contents of just water), would achieve incredible voltage at the circuit's resonant frequency. This effortlessly breaks down water (H2O) into combustible H2 and O (gas), thusly solving all energy problems. He was supposedly poisoned.

Google or Youtube "Stanley Meyer" or "Stan Meyer"
Be inspired.
I designed this in reference to Meyer's work, to the best of my understanding. His concept is totally possible, and inspired me to experiment with HHO for a few years now. In search of a way of creating such an object (the VIC), this is, ultimately, where I found Makerbot Industries.
It seems like everyone (outside the 3d-world) that tries to make one of these, just dosn't have the scope or dimensions right. I do plan on winding this transformer (manually, unless i get really smart and force makerbot do it for me), some day... and testing... someday.

The stl files that i uploaded I actually havent tested... I did my own, found out it was rather tight (I had to press the knife in), so i tweaked everything a bit larger so it should fit easier.
